<p>with your <code>secondEventLoop</code> object, and when configuring bindings for the second controller, pass it in to the trigger methods in <code>CommandXboxController</code></p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">EventLoop secondaryEventLoop = new EventLoop();
public void configureBindings() {
    secondController.b(secondaryEventLoop).onTrue(...);
    // ...
}
</code></pre>
<p>And when you want to switch I think you could just do</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">firstController.leftTrigger(.2).onTrue(
    Commands.runOnce(
        () -&gt; CommandScheduler.getInstance().setActiveButtonLoop(
            secondaryEventLoop)));
</code></pre>
<p>Just make sure you put the release trigger in the second event loop too</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">firstController.leftTrigger(.2, secondaryEventLoop).negate().onTrue(
        () -&gt; CommandScheduler.getInstance().setActiveButtonLoop(
            CommandScheduler.getInstance().getDefaultButtonLoop())));
</code></pre>
